MEASLES - UNITED KINGDOM: (ENGLAND, WALES)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 9 Jan 2009
Source: The Guardian online [edited]
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2009/jan/09/measles-record-numbers>


The number of measles cases in England and Wales hit a record high
last year [2008], sparking renewed fears of an epidemic. There were
1217 cases from January to November 2008 in England and Wales, the
highest number for 13 years, and the only time the number of cases
has exceeded 1000 in that period, according to the Health Protection
Agency (HPA). There were 990 measles cases reported in the whole of 2007.

The number of cases reported rose sharply in the autumn, with 115
cases reported in November 2008 alone, said the HPA, which monitors
infectious diseases. Worryingly, nearly 3/4th (74 percent) of the
cases diagnosed in that month were outside the traditional hotspot of
London in the West Midlands and the northwest and southeast of
England. Most of those cases are linked with measles outbreaks in
nurseries, primary and secondary schools. There have also been
outbreaks in traveler communities in the West Midlands and the southeast.

Dr Mary Ramsay, an HPA immunisation expert, said: "We are still
experiencing an unprecedented increase in measles cases across
England and Wales." More than 6 in 10 (65 percent) of all cases in
England and Wales were in children under the age of 15. The HPA said
measles was spreading more easily because of the relatively low
uptake of the MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) jab over the past
decade. Rates of vaccination in Britain slumped after an
unsubstantiated scare over the triple jab. There are about 3 million
children, one in 4 of whom have not had both MMR doses, which are
necessary to ensure they are fully protected. Ramsay said: "This
continued rise is due to relatively low MMR vaccine uptake over the
past decade, and there are now a large number of children who are not
fully protected with MMR. This means that measles, which is highly
infectious, is spreading easily among these unvaccinated children.
The agency is concerned that we may see measles epidemics take hold.
We again are urging parents to get their children vaccinated."

"Although MMR coverage is starting to improve, we cannot stress
enough that measles is serious, and in some cases it can be fatal.
Delaying immunisation puts children at risk. We are glad to see that
public confidence in the MMR vaccine is now high, with more than 8
out of 10 children receiving one dose of MMR by their 2nd birthday.
But we shouldn't forget that the children who weren't vaccinated many
years ago are at real risk. Measles is a very serious infection, as
it can lead to pneumonia and encephalitis, even in healthy children.
It is highly infectious and can be passed on without direct contact
before the rash appears."

Last year [2008], HPA research showed that, without a wider uptake of
the MMR vaccine, there was a real risk of a large measles epidemic of
between 30 000 to 100 000 cases, the majority in London. Earlier this
week, researchers warned that hopes of eradicating measles in Europe
by 2010 were in jeopardy due to poor vaccination rates in a handful
of countries including Britain. Doctors at the Statens Serum
Institute in Copenhagen, writing in the Lancet, said medical records
from 32 European countries confirmed 12 132 cases in 2006 and 2007,
the majority of which came from the UK, Germany, Switzerland, Italy
and Romania.

